25|$|One {{investigation}} {{of this kind}} was {{the study of the}} <b>waggle</b> dance ("dance language") in bee communication by Karl von Frisch. Lorenz subsequently developed a theory of the evolution of animal communication based on his observations of fixed action patterns and the circumstances in which they are expressed.|$|E
25|$|His work {{centered}} on {{investigations of the}} sensory perceptions of the honey bee {{and he was one}} of the first to translate the meaning of the <b>waggle</b> dance. His theory, described in his 1927 book Aus dem Leben der Bienen (translated into English as The Dancing Bees), was disputed by other scientists and greeted with skepticism at the time. Only much later was it shown to be an accurate theoretical analysis.|$|E
